│ stop({"edit_points": [[7573, 7576,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an assertion in             │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() which verifies that the VPlan-based │
│ cost model agrees with the legacy cost model. The assertion allows            │
│ disagreement only if the selected plan has early exits or the plan contains   │
│ additional simplifications not accounted for by the legacy cost model. In     │
│ this reproducer, VF choices disagree and none of the allowed conditions are   │
│ detected, triggering the assertion and aborting.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's        │
│ Log:\nScalarEvolution indicates a first-order recurrence (%for) that depends  │
│ on the previous value of %iv. The loop has a small bounded trip count. The    │
│ crash happens at computeBestVF() during the consistency check against the     │
│ legacy model. That suggests a mismatch in modeling, most likely around a      │
│ first-order recurrence handling where VPlan applies a simplification (e.g.,   │
│ scalarizing or removing certain FOR-related constructs) that the legacy cost  │
│ model does not account for.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe helper            │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(VPlan&, VPCostContext&, Loop*) is       │
│ responsible for detecting extra VPlan simplifications to avoid false          │
│ assertion failures. It iterates the IR and returns true if there are          │
│ instructions in the original loop not represented in the VPlan or skipped by  │
│ the VPlan cost model.\n\nHowever, it explicitly excludes all header PHI nodes │
│ from consideration:\n  if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())\n  │
│ return false;\nThis means if VPlan removes or simplifies a header PHI, such   │
│ as a First-Order Recurrence PHI (%for) being scalarized or transformed, the   │
│ helper cannot detect that simplification. Meanwhile, the legacy cost model    │
│ still accounts for costs related to that PHI (or its effects), causing a      │
│ disagreement in VF selection that isn’t recognized as a valid exception, and  │
│ thus the assertion fires.\n\nNote that the function already has special       │
│ handling for FOR splices using VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe: it returns    │
│ true if FOR has no splice users. But if the simplification manifests as the   │
│ header PHI being removed or represented differently, and no explicit VP       │
│ recipe maps to the original PHI, the current blanket exclusion of header PHIs │
│ prevents detection. In our reproducer, the VPlan likely simplified or         │
│ scalarized the FOR behavior, leading to a mismatch without setting the flag   │
│ that triggers the exception.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nTo ensure these   │
│ simplifications are detected, remove the unconditional exclusion of header    │
│ PHIs. That way, if a header PHI from the original loop is not represented in  │
│ the VPlan and not skipped by the cost context,                                │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications will return true, and the assertion     │
│ will not fire.\n\nEdit Point:\n- File:                                        │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp\n- Lines: 7573-7576\n-        │
│ Change: Remove the special-case exclusion of header PHI nodes so that missing │
│ header PHIs are considered as additional simplifications.\n\nOriginal:\n      │
│ if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())\n        return false;\n  │
│ return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I,           │
│ true);\n\nUpdated:\n      // Do not exclude header PHIs unconditionally; if a │
│ header PHI from the\n      // original loop is not represented in the VPlan   │
│ and not skipped by the\n      // cost context, treat it as an additional      │
│ simplification.\n      return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&                     │
│ !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true);\n\nRationale:\n- This conservative    │
│ change allows planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to correctly flag cases   │
│ where VPlan removes or transforms header PHIs (such as FOR PHIs), which the   │
│ legacy cost model may still account for.\n- It aligns the assertion’s         │
│ exception path with actual VPlan simplifications, preventing false assertion  │
│ failures.\n- The function already filters out instructions via                │
│ CostCtx.skipCostComputation, so induction PHIs or others that should be       │
│ ignored by VPlan cost modeling can still be skipped appropriately.\n\n5.      │
│ Conclusion:\nBy removing the unconditional exclusion of header PHIs from      │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications, we let the verification recognize      │
│ VPlan simplifications involving loop header PHIs (such as first-order         │
│ recurrence handling). This prevents the assertion from firing incorrectly     │
│ when the VPlan-based cost model picks a different VF due to simplifications   │
│ not modeled by the legacy cost model. The fix should make the reproducer stop │
│ aborting while preserving the intended verification behavior."})              │
