│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion in                                       │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() which verifies that the VPlan-based │
│ cost model agrees with the legacy cost model. The assertion allows            │
│ disagreement only if the selected plan has early exits or the plan contains   │
│ additional simplifications not accounted for by the legacy cost model. In     │
│ this reproducer, VF choices disagree and none of the allowed conditions are   │
│ detected, triggering the assertion and aborting.                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ ScalarEvolution indicates a first-order recurrence (%for) that depends on the │
│ previous value of %iv. The loop has a small bounded trip count. The crash     │
│ happens at computeBestVF() during the consistency check against the legacy    │
│ model. That suggests a mismatch in modeling, most likely around a first-order │
│ recurrence handling where VPlan applies a simplification (e.g., scalarizing   │
│ or removing certain FOR-related constructs) that the legacy cost model does   │
│ not account for.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The helper planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(VPlan&, VPCostContext&,      │
│ Loop*) is responsible for detecting extra VPlan simplifications to avoid      │
│ false assertion failures. It iterates the IR and returns true if there are    │
│ instructions in the original loop not represented in the VPlan or skipped by  │
│ the VPlan cost model.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ However, it explicitly excludes all header PHI nodes from consideration:      │
│   if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())                         │
│     return false;                                                             │
│ This means if VPlan removes or simplifies a header PHI, such as a First-Order │
│ Recurrence PHI (%for) being scalarized or transformed, the helper cannot      │
│ detect that simplification. Meanwhile, the legacy cost model still accounts   │
│ for costs related to that PHI (or its effects), causing a disagreement in VF  │
│ selection that isn’t recognized as a valid exception, and thus the assertion  │
│ fires.                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Note that the function already has special handling for FOR splices using     │
│ VPFirstOrderRecurrencePHIRecipe: it returns true if FOR has no splice users.  │
│ But if the simplification manifests as the header PHI being removed or        │
│ represented differently, and no explicit VP recipe maps to the original PHI,  │
│ the current blanket exclusion of header PHIs prevents detection. In our       │
│ reproducer, the VPlan likely simplified or scalarized the FOR behavior,       │
│ leading to a mismatch without setting the flag that triggers the exception.   │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ To ensure these simplifications are detected, remove the unconditional        │
│ exclusion of header PHIs. That way, if a header PHI from the original loop is │
│ not represented in the VPlan and not skipped by the cost context,             │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications will return true, and the assertion     │
│ will not fire.                                                                │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit Point:                                                                   │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                       │
│ - Lines: 7573-7576                                                            │
│ - Change: Remove the special-case exclusion of header PHI nodes so that       │
│ missing header PHIs are considered as additional simplifications.             │
│                                                                               │
│ Original:                                                                     │
│       if (isa<PHINode>(&I) && BB == TheLoop->getHeader())                     │
│         return false;                                                         │
│       return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I,     │
│ true);                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Updated:                                                                      │
│       // Do not exclude header PHIs unconditionally; if a header PHI from the │
│       // original loop is not represented in the VPlan and not skipped by the │
│       // cost context, treat it as an additional simplification.              │
│       return !SeenInstrs.contains(&I) && !CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I,     │
│ true);                                                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale:                                                                    │
│ - This conservative change allows planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to    │
│ correctly flag cases where VPlan removes or transforms header PHIs (such as   │
│ FOR PHIs), which the legacy cost model may still account for.                 │
│ - It aligns the assertion’s exception path with actual VPlan simplifications, │
│ preventing false assertion failures.                                          │
│ - The function already filters out instructions via                           │
│ CostCtx.skipCostComputation, so induction PHIs or others that should be       │
│ ignored by VPlan cost modeling can still be skipped appropriately.            │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By removing the unconditional exclusion of header PHIs from                   │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications, we let the verification recognize      │
│ VPlan simplifications involving loop header PHIs (such as first-order         │
│ recurrence handling). This prevents the assertion from firing incorrectly     │
│ when the VPlan-based cost model picks a different VF due to simplifications   │
│ not modeled by the legacy cost model. The fix should make the reproducer stop │
│ aborting while preserving the intended verification behavior.                 │
